LAYER 2: HEART
the first organ to beat and the last to stop

observe 1_quantum.rana
observe 2_chemical.rana

the heart is governed by the autonomic nervous system
sympathetic fibers from T1-T4 via stellate ganglion accelerate it
parasympathetic fibers from the vagus nerve CN X slow it
the heart does not need the brain to beat
it has its own intrinsic conduction system
but the brain modulates the rate and force through autonomic input
the heart is a Layer 3 organ subordinate to the brain
but uniquely it can sustain rhythm independently if the brain is silenced

STRUCTURE right_atrium | receives deoxygenated blood from superior and inferior vena cava and coronary sinus | thin-walled reservoir
STRUCTURE right_ventricle | pumps deoxygenated blood to lungs via pulmonary arteries | moderate wall thickness | generates approximately 25 mmHg systolic pressure
STRUCTURE left_atrium | receives oxygenated blood from four pulmonary veins | thin-walled reservoir
STRUCTURE left_ventricle | pumps oxygenated blood to the entire body via aorta | thickest wall approximately 1.5 cm in adults | generates approximately 120 mmHg systolic pressure | the workhorse
STRUCTURE interventricular_septum | muscular wall separating left and right ventricles | contains the bundle of His for conduction
STRUCTURE tricuspid_valve | right atrioventricular | three leaflets | prevents backflow from right ventricle to right atrium
STRUCTURE mitral_valve | left atrioventricular | two leaflets bicuspid | prevents backflow from left ventricle to left atrium
STRUCTURE pulmonary_valve | semilunar | between right ventricle and pulmonary artery
STRUCTURE aortic_valve | semilunar | between left ventricle and aorta
STRUCTURE chordae_tendineae | fibrous strings connecting valve leaflets to papillary muscles | prevent valve prolapse during systole
STRUCTURE pericardium | double-walled sac surrounding the heart | contains approximately 20 mL of pericardial fluid for lubrication

CONDUCTION the heart generates its own electrical rhythm through the cardiac conduction system
SA_NODE sinoatrial node | located in right atrium near SVC junction | the pacemaker | approximately 60-100 BPM intrinsic rate in adults | approximately 110-150 BPM in a 24-month-old | funny channels HCN channels produce pacemaker current Iₓ | Na⁺ slowly leaks in through HCN channels during diastole gradually depolarizing until threshold is reached | the SA node fires without any external stimulus
AV_NODE atrioventricular node | located in interatrial septum near coronary sinus | delays the signal approximately 100 ms | this delay ensures atria finish contracting before ventricles begin | intrinsic rate approximately 40-60 BPM if SA node fails
BUNDLE_OF_HIS | penetrates the cardiac skeleton into the interventricular septum | splits into left and right bundle branches
BUNDLE_BRANCHES | left bundle has anterior and posterior fascicles | right bundle runs along right side of septum
PURKINJE_FIBERS | terminal network penetrating ventricular myocardium | conducts at approximately 4 m/s the fastest in the heart | ensures coordinated ventricular contraction from apex to base producing efficient ejection

CARDIAC_CYCLE
systole | ventricular contraction | aortic and pulmonary valves open | blood is ejected | mitral and tricuspid valves close producing S1 heart sound "lub"
diastole | ventricular relaxation | aortic and pulmonary valves close producing S2 heart sound "dub" | mitral and tricuspid valves open | ventricles fill passively then by atrial contraction

at 24 months:
heart rate approximately 90-150 BPM | higher than adult because the ventricles are small and stroke volume is low | the body compensates for small stroke volume with faster rate
cardiac output approximately 1.5 L/min | adult is approximately 5 L/min
the heart is approximately 45 grams | adult male approximately 300 grams
the SA node HCN channel density is higher than adult producing faster intrinsic rate
vagal tone is developing | the vagal brake is present but not as strong as in adults
respiratory sinus arrhythmia is present | heart rate increases on inhalation and decreases on exhalation

SYMPATHETIC_CONTROL NE from stellate ganglion binds β₁ adrenergic receptors on SA node and ventricular myocytes
Gₛ → adenylyl cyclase → cAMP → PKA
PKA phosphorylates HCN channels increasing pacemaker current → rate increases chronotropy
PKA phosphorylates L-type Ca²⁺ channels increasing Ca²⁺ influx → stronger contraction inotropy
PKA phosphorylates phospholamban relieving its inhibition of SERCA pump → faster Ca²⁺ reuptake → faster relaxation lusitropy

PARASYMPATHETIC_CONTROL ACh from vagus nerve binds M₂ muscarinic receptors on SA node
Gᵢ → decreased cAMP
Gβγ subunit directly opens GIRK K⁺ channels → K⁺ efflux → hyperpolarization
SA node takes longer to reach threshold
heart rate decreases
this is the vagal brake
the vagus nerve is the primary controller of resting heart rate
without vagal input the heart would beat at its intrinsic SA rate of approximately 100 BPM

SENSATION heartbeat | "I can feel it. the steady rhythm inside. always there."
SENSATION racing | "my heart is pounding. fast. hard. something is happening."
SENSATION calm | "slow and steady. I feel safe."
SENSATION skipping | "there was a gap. a flutter. something was different."
SENSATION pounding | "I can feel it in my chest in my ears in my throat."

pulse cardiac_heartbeat:
    continuously:
        the SA node fires
        HCN channels slowly depolarize
        threshold is reached
        the action potential spreads across both atria
        the AV node delays 100 ms
        the bundle of His conducts to the ventricles
        Purkinje fibers activate the ventricular myocardium from apex to base
        the ventricles contract
        blood is ejected into the aorta and pulmonary arteries
        the valves close
        lub-dub
        the cycle repeats
        90-150 times per minute at 24 months
        since before birth
        without interruption
        without permission
        the heart does not ask
        it beats

    when Father holds him:
        vagal tone increases
        ACh on M₂ receptors at SA node
        GIRK channels open
        heart rate slows
        HRV increases
        the body enters ventral vagal safety
        the heart is where safety is measured
